<subSubSection id="819A1969059084819F46217B8E10BCE7" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="variation">
<paragraph id="2057448C1B4F026344E945DE4873D83F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Variation.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6A205460B961F0C08ACCC996DC46C9DD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="13AE23D2812EC45F00FEBE7DF05E0667" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. lui" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="lui">
<emphasis id="8E6EBC2594B0A4F8F3067B308AFB3163" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. lui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. display great variation in color. Some are totally black except for yellowish brown legs and abdomens (Fig. F, G); a few individuals are mainly black but pronota are reddish brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F554BA22CAC9F342A9FD01ADE8F2DA6D" captionStart="Figure 41" captionStartId="F41" captionText="Figure 41. Habitus of Pyrrhalta lui sp. nov. A male, typical form, dorsal view B ditto, ventral view C ditto, lateral view D female, dorsal view E ditto, ventral view F male, color variation, dorsal view G ditto, ventral view H male, color variation, dorsal view I ditto, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure41" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545571" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">41H, I</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C42B07E905D012FFFBB3BB970AAD4A9E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="331293DE8EB7121BD437CB1CEB751D79" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5013C5F63FF5D9E0BFFD3E27D2B1837C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Adults of 
<taxonomicName id="EC0D9D07FA8145431540B1F1956D633D" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. lui" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="lui">
<emphasis id="168CDAE7DBE6E23F8C7321255705E554" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. lui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. are distinguished within the species group by unicolorous elytra. In males, the aedeagus (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="772398230E72EE2A964C421B7AE266BD" captionStart="Figure 40" captionStartId="F40" captionText="Figure 40. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta jungchani sp. nov. and P. lui sp. nov. on host plant A adult of P. jungchani sp. nov. B host plant for P. lui sp. nov., Viburnum parvifolium with feeding marks C adult of P. lui sp. nov. feeding on leaves of V. luzonicum D adult of P. lui sp. nov." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545570" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">40C, D</figureCitation>
) is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="C69398B2AD7903E99290BDEAE74D2CF2" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. jungchani" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="jungchani">
<emphasis id="EFB2B60AC45D16D5189D20043AFFFA70" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. jungchani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A99BE1EE241D2D4D2ABE59D7FC6B569D" captionStart="Figure 39" captionStartId="F39" captionText="Figure 39. Diagnostic characters of Pyrrhalta jungchani sp. nov. A antenna, male B antenna, female C aedeagus, dorsal view D ditto, lateral view E abdominal ventrite VIII F apex of tibia of middle leg, male G gonocoxae H tarsi of middle leg, male I abdominal ventrite V, female J abdominal ventrite V, male K spermatheca." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure39" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545569" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">39C, D</figureCitation>
), with an asymmetrically lanceolate shape and two endophallic sclerites. It differs by the straight apex and the longer secondary endophallic sclerite, 0.6 
<normalizedToken id="88B20FAE2D1DD6EF3B5720044E47DEC0" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as primary endophallic sclerite (recurved apex and shorter secondary endophallic sclerite, 0.3 
<normalizedToken id="DCF17536A975CCA91925EE8F80CF634F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as primary endophallic sclerite, in 
<taxonomicName id="349D4BD87381AA69D2374657BC780EEA" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Rosaceae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="P. jungchani" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="jungchani">
<emphasis id="C617861C7EDD810BCBAC054A60614DAD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">P. jungchani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="88A4AD9F2B03A3E3C56F227BA0CAE908" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="food plants">
<paragraph id="4084F7244AB178E0D2981FB60AC33594" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Food plants.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FFC85DB7BB6325D6ED59C542D55A85D2" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Adults feed on leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="14B0486A626AAC9E0E55786B7A08531A" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Adoxaceae" genus="Viburnum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Viburnum parvifolium" order="Dipsacales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="parvifolium">
<emphasis id="B87FB18F7AC8EF007D6550FC2B508687" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Viburnum parvifolium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hayata (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="50028B52B56DA998E3BF5A286451946B" captionStart="Figure 40" captionStartId="F40" captionText="Figure 40. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta jungchani sp. nov. and P. lui sp. nov. on host plant A adult of P. jungchani sp. nov. B host plant for P. lui sp. nov., Viburnum parvifolium with feeding marks C adult of P. lui sp. nov. feeding on leaves of V. luzonicum D adult of P. lui sp. nov." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545570" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">40B</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="141486A427ACF2400DB498C9F002663C" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Adoxaceae" genus="V." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="V. luzonicum" order="Dipsacales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="luzonicum">
<emphasis id="A2F3CBC78AB520EA5E5A72DD736F3055" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">V. luzonicum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Rolfe (
<taxonomicName id="836936F9C07C3E5F8A2497DCD7116489" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Adoxaceae" genus="V." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Dipsacales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="family">Adoxaceae</taxonomicName>
) (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E8BECADE1C4DEDDDEC5D61F48B6177AA" captionStart="Figure 40" captionStartId="F40" captionText="Figure 40. Field photographs of Pyrrhalta jungchani sp. nov. and P. lui sp. nov. on host plant A adult of P. jungchani sp. nov. B host plant for P. lui sp. nov., Viburnum parvifolium with feeding marks C adult of P. lui sp. nov. feeding on leaves of V. luzonicum D adult of P. lui sp. nov." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1039.64740.figure40" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545570" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">40C, D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="14265BDF729C1B65D52AE3701BE93F51" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="AB5456132A1FE9EAAF20DE3C1FB54EF5" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="198EC600561158B34C87CB256B046581" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">The species is widespread at mid-altitudes (1,500-2,500 m) in central and southern Taiwan.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
